<TEXT>
a soviet emigrant with links to israeli 
politicians and military officers went on trial monday insisting 
his confession of spying for the soviet union was obtained under 
duress his lawyer said 
shabtai kalmanovich 43 was taken into the closed courtroom 
under heavy guard he stopped briefly to embrace his father and 
wife who handed him newspapers cigarettes and a sack of cheese and 
lettuce sandwichs 
attorney amnon zichroni said his client took extensive notes 
during the fivehour hearing he said only one witness testified 
monday an agent of shin bet israels secret service who helped 
obtain kalmanovichs confession during his eight months in custody 
we are arguing that this confession was not made 
voluntarily zichroni told the associated press i am not 
permitted to give details but i can say we oppose its 
submission 
the exact charges kalmanovich faces have not been revealed he 
is expected to plead innocent after the hearing resumes thursday 
kalmanovich who emigrated from the soviet union in 1971 was 
arrested in december he had established himself in israel as an 
international businessman an activist in the labor party and a 
socialite who mixed with leading politicians and senior army 
officers 
zichroni declined to comment on foreign reports that the soviet 
union may be working on a deal to trade kalmanovich in a spy swap 
involving jonathan jay pollard an american convicted of spying for 
israel and another unidentified american 
kalmanovich wore sneakers and was dressed neatly monday but had 
long hair the security men dont take me to the barber he 
told reporters 
</TEXT>
