<TEXT>
us military forces in south korea are helping 
to protect the olympic games the writer the associated press 
bureau chief in seoul went on a us air force flight to get a 
view of the preparations 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
capt john vandervalk 
scanned the target and flung the plane in a stomachwrenching 
attack dive into the rocky valley below 
the small us air force ov10 bronco nosedived the force of 
the acceleration forcing its two occupants back against their 
armorplated seats hills flashed past as vandervalk streaked 
toward the target calmly checking the attack coordinates 
white phosphorous rockets flashed from the planes belly and 
slammed into the practice target as the pilot jerked the plane up 
over a rock cliff vandervalk glanced back to check his handiwork 
we do everything as if it were day one of a war except nobody 
shoots at us vandervalk explained after thursdays flight you 
really have a sense of urgency and mission in korea 
us forces stationed in south korea are on increased alert in 
case communist north korea makes any attempt to disrupt the olympic 
games which begin sept 17 in seoul the united states is helping 
guarantee the security of the olympics 
vandervalk and other pilots of the air forces 19th tactical air 
control squadron serve as forward air controllers whose mission is 
to spot and mark targets with smoke for other planes to attack 
their small planes also fly attack missions against ground targets 
we control violence is the motto worn by members of the 
squadron based at osan air force base south of seoul 
hundreds of thousands of troops including 42000 us troops 
face each other in a tense confrontation on the demilitarized zone 
that divides the peninsula 
us forces have been based in south korea since the united 
states intervened to help the south after north korea invaded in 
1950 to begin the korean war an armistice was signed in 1953 but 
the north and south technically are still at war 
col bob hammond commander of the 5th tactical air control 
group said the north korean threat is a daily fact of life 
i think the threat presented by the north koreans is real 
they are not what could be classified as rational actors he said 
south korean and us commanders fear north korea will attempt 
to disrupt the olympics because its demand to be a cohost of the 
games has been rejected the north has a long history of launching 
terrorist attacks against the south 
the north koreans would like to see an embarrassment to the 
republic of south korea and the united states hammond said 
us troops wont be guarding olympic venues but the games have 
increased the sense of tension and spurred greater vigilance 
hammond said 
everyones adrenalin goes up everyone leans forward in their 
foxholes hammond said 
airspace over seoul and all olympic sites has been declared 
offlimits during the games south korean military air controllers 
quickly challenge any approaching plane 
if you get real close to the capital area they threaten to 
shoot you down vandervalk said after being challenged by an air 
controller over the radio 
vandervalk who has been stationed in south korea for three 
years said training is intense because hostile forces are poised 
just a few miles away pilots carry war plans on all missions 
were ready to go to work at a moments notice he said 
flying over nightmare range about 15 miles from the border 
vandervalk pointed out a north korean military air base visible 
across the border 
the north korean migs can be on us in two minutes he said 
vandervalk said he has not seen a north korean jet during his 
tour of duty in the south but he and other pilots often hear the 
norths military radio traffic while they are flying 
the airwaves along the border constantly crackle with south 
korean and us military air controllers giving instructions the 
area routinely is busy with warplanes on patrol or practicing 
south koreans have to live with a constant military presence and 
frequent exercises that can be disruptive but they accept the 
inconveniences as unavoidable vandervalk said 
it shows how lucky people in the west are he said when 
was the last time an american had a tank roll through his garden 
</TEXT>
