a 76yearold woman was placed in suspended 
animation nearly an hour as surgeons removed an eggsized aneurysm 
from the base of her brain hospital officials said 
cecilia duffy of pittsburgh remained comatose sunday and listed 
in critical condition four days after the unusual operation said 
judy secreto an allegheny general hospital spokeswoman 
its not uncommon for it to last a couple of days ms 
secreto said 
surgeons removed the aneurysm from ms duffys brain after 
dropping her body temperature by 40 degrees and draining the blood 
from her body her heart was stopped during wednesdays operation 
the coma was induced by barbiturates to protect the brain while 
blood flow was suspended said ms secreto 
dr julian e bailes a neurosurgeon said ms duffy fit the 
legal criteria for brain death during the 51 minutes of suspended 
animation 
the aneurysm a bubble in the blood vessel caused by weakness in 
the vessel wall was suctioned out while ms duffy was on the 
bypass machine 
any more pressure by the aneurysm would have compressed on the 
vital centers of the brain stem and her heart would have stopped 
or she would have gone into a coma and died bailes said 
im still worried about her but objectively speaking there 
is a good chance she may pull through this thing he said 
postsurgical scans showed increased brain activity and ms 
duffy was moving her legs when touched according to bailes but 
he said theres such a fine line between a perfect outcome and 
her never waking up thats the hard thing 
ms duffy had become almost completely disabled during the past 
year because of the aneurysm 
