<TEXT>
the trades union congress voted 
overwhelmingly today to expel the electricians union its first 
ouster of an affiliate in 15 years 
delegates of the electricians 336000member union showed their 
disdain by walking out en masse minutes before the trades union 
took its vote the vote by a show of hands came on the opening 
morning of the trades unions weeklong annual conference in this 
south england seaside resort 
the electronic telecommunication and plumbing union was ousted 
for signing two singleunion nostrike deals with management in 
violation of trades union policy 
more than 30 singleunion nostrike deals have been struck in 
britain with one union representing all the workers at a plant and 
disputes submitted to binding arbitration 
the trades union believes such deals weaken union bargaining 
power and lead to competition among unions for representation in a 
shrinking job market 
some predicted the expulsion would create a ripple effect 
confronting the 9million member national labor federation with 
what the financial times called the most serious split in british 
trade union history 
it also raised the prospect of the electricians and other 
rebellious unions forming a rival labor federation among those 
siding with the electricians union is the amalgamated engineering 
union the trades unions second biggest affiliate 
delegates shouted down engineers leader bill jordan and the 
microphone was cut off when he urged a postponement of the 
electricians expulsion saying it would inflict grievous bodily 
harm 
electricians leader eric hammond in a defiant final speech to 
the conference before the vote accused leftwing unions of 
conspiring to bring about the expulsion spoke of witch hunts 
and portrayed his union as a david fighting a goliath 
trades union general secretary norman willis addressing the 
representatives of the 85 affiliate unions denied any witch hunt 
and said the electricians union had refused every opportunity to 
scrap the nostrike deals 
the electricians union was suspended july 8 after accepting 
nostrike deals at two plants in lancashire and south wales 
todays vote converted the suspension to outright expulsion 
in the last expulsion in 1973 10 unions were ousted for 
refusing to oppose government legislation on industrial relations 
eight of the unions rejoined the trades union after the legislation 
was repealed 
</TEXT>
