<TEXT>
shipping companies the coast guard and the 
army corps of engineers are joining in an unprecedented effort to 
ensure that the droughtcaused bottlenecks that idled mississippi 
river traffic this summer wont recur a shipping industry 
executive says 
the three groups are forming a task force and establishing a 
clearinghouse at cincinnait to share information about the 
mississippi and ohio rivers according to jeffrey smith vice 
president of a shipping industry group called american waterway 
operators 
the drought smith said has cost the industry an estimated 200 
million about 20 percent of its annual operating revenue 
however the worst of the 1988 drought may be past for those who 
work on or live along the river some officials believe 
an underwater dike built by the corps for example has stopped 
saltwater from creeping up the mississippi and fouling the water 
supply for new orleans however the corps has had to supply by 
barge some downriver communities with millions of gallons of fresh 
water 
at new orleans the river is running at a rate of about 130000 
cubic feet per second about 55 percent of normal for this time of 
year in early july however it was closer to 114000 
were still way below average said roger steakely a corps 
spokesman in vicksburg miss but were not nearly as bad as we 
were 
gulf of mexico waters have pushed their way up the 
droughtreduced river turning the muddy brown water a beautiful 
bluegreen and threatening the water supply for new orleans which 
is about 100 miles from the mouth of the mississippi 
because the salty water is heavier than the fresh mississippi 
water the corps decided to impede the flow by building a dirt dam 
15 to 25 feet high across the river bottom 
the 790000 structure about 30 miles south of new orleans 
succeeded in heading off the salty flow it was too late however 
for some small communities in plaquemines parish where the corps 
continues to deliver bargeloads of water from farther upriver 
by the middle of last week the corps had barged 52 million 
gallons for those communities according to bruce sossaman a 
