<TEXT>
five years and more than 150 million in legal 
fees later a giant fraud case stemming from the biggest default in 
the history of the municipal bond market is headed for trial 
wednesday in tucson ariz 
the litigation in federal court is a consolidation of dozens of 
lawsuits filed by bondholders after the washington public power 
supply systems 1983 default on 225 billion in bonds sold to 
finance construction of two nuclear power plants 
though it has remained obscure the socalled whoops case 
has won notoriety in legal and financial circles for its size and 
complexity 
consider 
since about 1980 market defaults have totaled about 57 
billion forty percent of that is wppss said c richard 
lehmann of miami lakes fla treasurer of the national wppss 45 
bondholders committee 
dozens of attorneys from some 70 law firms with rates as high 
as 400 an hour have been involved in pretrial work still to be 
added to the legal tab are trial costs and the fees of many 
attorneys who have worked for five years on contingency 
a computerized dataretrieval system for the plaintiffs side 
alone has cost more than 35 million and it holds 14 million 
documents and hundreds of statements by witnesses the defense is 
keeping its system secret 
more than 24000 claims have been filed by an estimated 42000 
bondholders 
defendants from wall street bond underwriting firms to 88 
public utilities to law firms and economic advisers originally 
numbered more than 100 some including bond underwriters have 
settled outside court for 331 million so far wppss itself was let 
out of the suit last week in a surprise move leaving 21 utilities 
and engineering and financial adviser firms as defendants 
the trial itself could last up to two years 
the wppss case is unique said new york university professor 
