pernod ricard sa the french drinks company said 
monday it made a friendly takeover offer of 285 million irish 
punts the equivalent of 412 million for irish distillers group 
plc to counter a hostile bid by the british liquor group grand 
metropolitan plc 
pernod claims to have received assurances from 518 percent of 
the irish whiskey makers shareholders to sell their shares to 
pernod irish distillers spokesman pat heneghan said 
pernod confirmed it had made a 450 pence 650 a share bid 
but declined to comment further before making its official 
announcement 
trading in shares of irish distillers was suspended monday at 
the companys request before the official opening of londons 
international stock market shares were suspended at 366 british 
pence 617 each equal to their friday closing price 
the suspension followed grand metropolitans announcement late 
sunday that it had raised its takeover bid to 332 million irish 
punts 480 million from 253 million punts 366 million in 
anticipation of pernods offer 
pernod also said monday it would challenge the decision of a 
british board which regulates mergers and acquisitions to allow 
grand metropolitan to raise its bid 
the french company will appeal the decision before britains 
independent takeover panel whose executive board allowed the 
raised bid on sunday said anthony beevor director general of the 
panel and a member of its executive board 
in dublin irish commerce minister albert reynolds said the 
takeover situation would also be examined by irelands fair trades 
commission in terms of its impact on employment competition and 
the common good 
the dublinbased irish distillers said friday it was holding 
talks with pernod which has boosted its holding to five percent of 
the companys shares from 28 percent 
pernod has said it would allow irish distillers to operate as an 
independent component of the pernodricard group maintaining the 
integrity of the irish whiskey industry 
the grand met bid is worth 525 irish pence 758 a share up 
from 400 pence 578 grand met said monday it now owns an 
819percent stake in irish distillers the largest maker of irish 
whiskey 
